{
  "local_port": 37612,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the procedure to file RTI?",
  "response": "Filing a Right to Information (RTI) application in India is a straightforward process that allows citizens to seek information from public authorities. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to filing an RTI:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Identify the Concerned Public Authority**\n   - Determine the specific government department, office, or public authority that holds the information you seek.\n   - For example, if you want information about a land record, the concerned authority could be the local Revenue Department.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Draft the RTI Application**\n   - Write the application in simple and clear language. There is **no prescribed format** for an RTI application, but it should include the following details:\n     - Your name, address, and contact details\n     - Specific details of the information you seek\n     - The period for which you require the information (if applicable)\n     - Whether you need the information in hard copy or soft copy\n   - Be precise and concise in your request.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Pay the Required Fee**\n   - For most applicants, the fee for an RTI application is **\u20b910**.\n   - Payment can be made via:\n     - Cash (attach a self-attested copy of the receipt)\n     - Demand Draft (DD)\n     - Indian Postal Order (IPO)\n     - Some states allow online payment through RTI portals.\n   - **BPL (Below Poverty Line) cardholders are exempt** from paying the fee but must attach a copy of their BPL card.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Submit the Application**\n   - You can submit the RTI application in one of the following ways:\n     - **In Person**: Visit the office of the concerned Public Information Officer (PIO) and submit the application.\n     - **Post**: Send the application via registered post or speed post to the PIO\u2019s address.\n     - **Online**: Many states have online RTI portals. Visit the official RTI website (e.g., [RTI Online Portal](https://rtionline.gov.in)) and follow the instructions to file the application.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Await a Response**\n   - The Public Information Officer (PIO) is legally required to respond within **30 days** of receiving the application.\n   - If the information concerns life or liberty, the response must be provided within **48 hours**.\n\n---\n\n### **6. Follow-Up (if Necessary)**\n   - If you don\u2019t receive a response within the stipulated time or are dissatisfied with the reply, you can:\n     - File a **First Appeal** with the First Appellate Authority (FAA) within 30 days of receiving the response or after the 30-day deadline.\n     - If the First Appeal is unsuccessful, you can file a **Second Appeal** with the Central Information Commission (CIC) or the respective State Information Commission (SIC).\n\n---\n\n### **7. Online RTI Portals**\n   - For central government departments, use the [RTI Online Portal](https://rtionline.gov.in).\n   - Many states also have their own RTI portals for state-level applications.\n\n---\n\n### **Important Notes**\n   - Ensure that your request adheres to the RTI Act and does not seek exempted information (e.g., matters of national security, personal privacy, etc.).\n   - Keep a copy of your application and proof of submission for future reference.\n\nThis procedure empowers citizens to access information and promote transparency in governance.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
